An unknown assailant sets off a grenade, killing 5 refugees.  The refugees then riot.
Violent demonstrations and riots in Goma over robberies by Zairian soldiers.  Civilian mobs carjack aid workers.  The violence causes Japan to withdraw its peacekeepers in the area.

issuenote: Militant and mob violence in the refugee camps leads to 6 deaths.  Three foreign doctors are also killed.

A strike called by opposition leader Etienne Tshisekedi turns Kinshasa into a ghost town.

issuenote: Civil servants strike over back wages.
Refugees stone aid workers to protest a reduction in food rations.

issuenote: A series of protests erupts after the interim parliament announces that the first general elections in a decade would be postponed for another two years.

Factional violence erupts near refugee camps.  Local Hunde tribesmen attack Hutus, Hutus attack Tutsis, and Zairian soldiers fight everyone, looting and robbing as they go.

A lieutenant colonel in a special army unit dies when he tries to disarm a drunken soldier with a grenade.  The deaths trigger rioting between two army units that leave at least 50 dead, mostly civilians.
Armed Hutus with rifles and machetes hunt down hundreds of Tutsis who had hidden in a Zairian church, killing at least 12.
Unknown gunmen ambush a military convoy, killing 7.
Angry Zairian soldiers blockade the airport to demand that troops wounded by unknown gunmen be transferred by plane to Kinshasa.
Hostile elements cross the border from Uganda, killing 30 villagers.
Unknown gunmen attack a Red Cross warehouse.

Armed men raid Bambu, killing between 50 and 60 civilians.  The violence is ethnic in nature, although the factions are not reported.
Students protest and riot, demanding that the prime minister step down.  They also protest outside the Burundi embassy to protest against the Tutsi-controlled government there.

More than 10,000 students storm through the capital in stolen vehicles to demand the resignation of the prime minister.  They condemn and attack foreign journalists, accusing them of being Rwandans.  Government forces shoot dead three students.
notes: Rwanda is invading Zaire in support of rebel movements.

issuenote: Carrying the coffin of a slain student over their heads, rioting students storm Parliament to demand the resignation of the prime minister, accused of allowing rebels to take over eastern Zaire.  Protests continue the next day.

About 5000 protesters take to the streets demanding that Etienne Tshisekedi be returned to the prime minister's office.  Police use clubs.

Protesters gather outside the home of Etienne Tshisekedi, the main opposition leader, to demand that Mobutu resign.  They also cheer for the rebel leader Laurent Kabila.

Egyptian human rights organization suspends all activities in Egypt in protest against what it saw as a government campaign of harassment against it.
Thousands of Egyptian citizens, including professionals, university students and schoolchildren, demonstrate in several cities across Egypt in protest against the the British.
Central Bank employees go on strike.
notes: Very little information on the strike was available, as it was only briefly mentioned in connection with another story.

issuenote: Six thousand lawyers protest in the street outside their syndicate after anti-riot police, some armed with batons and rifles, prevented the lawyers from entering at the behest of the government.
Four thousand students at Cairo University protest against Serbian attacks on Kosovo Muslims and call on Arabs and Muslims worldwide to unite to bring the crisis to an end.
Muslim extremists open fire on police in a village in the Assiut region of Upper Egypt, leaving two dead (one policeman and one of the extremists) and two policemen injured.
Three unidentified gunmen shoot and kill a Coptic priest at his monastery's farm.
Armed assailant shot dead by presidential bodyguards after attacking and wounding the Egyptian president with a knife while he was on a tour of northern Egypt.

Soccer fans angered by their team's loss go on a rampage, damaging a car, shop windows, and the nearby local headquarters of President Mubarak's National Party; police respond with tear gas and detain 99 fans.

elocal: El-Kusheh, Dar el-Salam, Awlad Toq West
issuenote: Dispute between a Muslim street vendor and a Christian shop owner sets off rioting that spreads to several nearby villages.  Police seal off all three villages.
notes: There are conflicting reports on the number of deaths. Also, Npart is an estimate and may indeed be higher (101 to 1,000).

issuenote: About 3,000 villagers riot, hurling rocks at motorists and setting vehicles ablaze after a speeding truck killed a 16-year-old girl.  Protesters demanded a crackdown on motorists who routinely ignore traffic rules along the route.
About 250 people riot against a police crackdown on contraband goods, overturning a police car but leaving no one hurt.

Villagers clash with police, hurl rocks at a passing train, and set three buses on fire after one of three speeding buses that had been racing each other veered off the road into a group of girls walking to school, killing two of the girls.

The wives of three Islamist journalists jailed for libeling a government minister they said had collaborated with Israel began a sit-in in front of the attorney general's office.  They were joined by several Labor Party leaders.

About 8,000 students of Al-Azhar University take to the streets and clash with police, damaging over a dozen police cars and injuring three officers, demanding the resignation of Egypt's culture minister for publishing a novel.

actor1: Rival factions within Hizb al-Amal (Labor Party)
target1: Rival factions within Hizb al-Amal (Labor Party)
issuenote: Thousands of political activists gathered for two separate meetings in different locations in Cairo to support two rival chairmen involved in a power struggle for leadership of Hizb al-Amal (The Labor Party).
Around 30 journalists, members of Egypt's Press Syndicate, begin a sit-in to protest the government's suspension of the opposition newspaper Al Shaab.
Nearly 200 workers at a Nestle factory in Cairo stage a sit-in protest over a pay dispute with management.
notes: Start and end dates are estimates.

issuenote: Tens of thousands of university students across the country engage in almost daily mass protests against Israeli actions against Palestinians and the Sharm el-Sheikh summit hosted by Egypt.
Fourteen killed, dozens wounded in violence surrounding Egypt's parliamentary elections.  The fighting, which took place near polling stations across the country.

At least 20 journalists covering Egypt's parliamentary elections for both foreign and local media reported being attacked by policemen and plainclothes security men, as well as by some civilians, over the course of four-week election period.
Around 3,000 students at Cairo University demonstrated peacefully against Israel and Israeli Prime Minister Ariel Sharon under police surveillance without incident.

Leaders of Egypt's journalists' union and leaders of the Cairo-based Arab lawyers' union call a short, symbolic work stoppage to mark what Arabs call Al-Nakba, or the catastrophe of the creation of Israel.

Over 1,000 Coptic Christians protest and riot inside Cairo's Abbasiya cathedral compound, angered by the publication by Al-Nabaa newspaper of pictures of a monk having sex with women inside a monastery in Assiut in southern Egypt.
notes: The bulk of the rioting took place in Cairo, and most reports only mention the riots in Cairo, but there is some brief mention of rioting taking place in Assiut, though almost no details are provided.

issuenote: Over 1,000 Coptic Christians protest and riot inside Cairo's Abbasiya cathedral compound, angered by the publication by Al-Nabaa newspaper of pictures of a monk having sex with women inside a monastery in Assiut in southern Egypt.

issuenote: Over 3,000 unemployed college graduates protest a government decision restricting new public sector jobs and training places to people under 28 years old.

Nearly 2,000 Egyptians gather on a square chanting anti-Israeli slogans while calling for jihad (holy war) against the Jewish state, in reaction to the killing two days prior of eight Palestinians in an Israeli attack.

Egyptians honor a Palestinian-declared labor strike to protest against Israel's seizure of Orient House, a building described in the article as the nerve center for Palestinian nationalist aspirations in Jerusalem.
About 2,000 rioters block the main road from Cairo to Alexandria and riot after a 16-year-old schoolgirl is killed by a motorist.
notes: Police listed as secondary target because reports indicate that villagers were angered over lax enforcement of traffic laws, which has led to frequent traffic-related deaths.

target1: United States and its NATO allies
issuenote: Thousands of Egyptian citizens and university students across Egypt hold demonstrations denouncing U.S. and NATO actions in Afghanistan and the Egyptian government's support of those actions.
Muslim and Coptic Christian villagers clash at the inauguration of a new Christian church after an argument over the volume of the church's bells.

Hundreds of thousands of Egyptians hold massive demonstrations and riots on university campuses and mosques across Egypt in outrage at continuing Palestinian-Israeli violence and in opposition to U.S. actions against Iraq.

target1: Deceased head of the Muslim Brotherhood, Mustafa Mashhir
issuenote: Some 50,000 mourners of Mustafa Mashhir, head of the Muslim Brotherhood who died at the age of 83 following a stroke, march quietly from a Cairo mosque to the cemetery where Mashhur was laid to rest in a massive show of solidarity with the MB.
About 1,000 villagers riot, blocking a main road and throwing debris on railroad tracks, after a car struck and killed two girls.
Hundreds of thousands of citizens hold massive demonstrations across the country in protest against the start of the U.S.-led war in Iraq.  In the last weeks, protests begin to turn violent.
Dozens of members of the leftist Tagammu opposition party rally outside the Egyptian parliament to protest the rising cost of living in Egypt, which they blame on government economic policies.

Thousands of Egyptian citizens, including journalists, political activists, and university students, hold demonstrations in Cairo and on several university campuses in protest against Israeli attacks on Palestinians and the occupation of Iraq.

Eleven people injured, four homes and eight market stalls of Coptic Christians burned during a brawl that took place in the village of Gazra (near Cairo) over rumors that Copts were planning to build a new church in the village.
notes: Number of participants is an estimate

issuenote: Nearly 100 members of Egypt's main opposition parties gather in the capital's to petition the president for constitutional reforms, economic reforms, and an end to restrictions on political parties and on press freedoms.
Thousands of students and Muslim women hold several peaceful demonstrations over a span of two months in protest against the French ban on the hijab (head scarf).

actor1: American University in Cairo (AUC) students and faculty
issuenote: American University in Cairo (AUC) students and faculty, including the president of the university, hold a rally to demand that Israel free AUC student Qassam Barghuti, son of arrested West Bank Fatah leader Marwan Barghuti.

A band of about 50 armed men led by clan leader Izzat Mohammed Hamid seize 160 hostages in the village of Nakhilah during a shootout with police who had been trying to arrest fugitives wanted for drug trafficking and other crimes.

About 3,000 students demonstrate at Alexandria University in protest against an Israeli police raid at the Al-Aqsa mosque compound in Jerusalem, Islam's third holiest site, a day earlier.  Three students were arrested by police.
Around 5,000 students at Menoufia (Menoufia) University demonstrate in protest against U.S. plans for democracy in the Middle East, its support for Israel, and its occupation of Iraq.
Several hundred people gather in Cairo's central Tahrir square to mark the one-year anniversary of the U.S.-led invasion of Iraq and to denounce the U.S. occupation of Iraq.
notes: Organizers placed the number of demonstrators at 2,000, while police estimated between 400 and 1,500 people were in attendance.

issuenote: Tens of thousands of university students on campuses across the country protest the Israeli assassination of Sheik Ahmed Yassin and the subsequent cancellation of the Arab summit in Tunisia.

Hundreds of students at Alexandria University and about 500 men at Al-Azhar mosque in Cairo protest U.S.-led sieges on Iraqi cities such as those in Fallujah and Najaf, express their solidarity with the rebel groups fighting U.S. forces in Iraq

About 50 Egyptian lawyers and journalists protest against the abuses of Iraqi detainees by U.S. soldiers and demand that U.S. Ambassador David C. Welch be kicked out of Egypt and that the soldiers involved be brought to justice.

Fifty-six Egyptian and Palestinian prisoners at the Gharbaniyat prison near Alexandria engage in a hunger strike during the Arab League summit in Tunisia, saying they were being held for political reasons and demanding their freedom.

target2: Governments of other Arab League member states
issuenote: In a small demonstration organized by several opposition parties, protesters gathered in front of the Arab League's Cairo headquarters as a summit of the Arab League was opening in Tunisia.
Tarek al-Zomor, an Egyptian Islamist imprisoned for his involvement in the assassination of former president Sadat stages, a hunger strike over his conditions.

Around 100 demonstrators protest outside Egypt's supreme court in Cairo to urge authorities to halt the use of torture across the country.  The event was organized by several human rights groups and opposition parties.
A confrontation between local police and villagers breaks out as a police officer leads a team in an attempt to evacuate villagers from a sports center built on land owned by that officer.

target1: United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)

Three simultaneous bomb attacks in two resort towns in Egypt's Sinai peninsula leave 32 dead, many of them Israeli tourists, and damage a Hilton resort.
About 300 people, including some Islamic and Christian leaders, stage a march to condemn the recent bombings in Taba.  The demonstration was organized by a Cairo-based Muslim youth organization.

Around 5,000 Egyptian pilgrims stranded for several days at the port of Nuweiba stage a protest against the poor living conditions there and demand that authorities allow them immediately to continue their journey to Mecca.

The editor of the Nasserist Al-Arabi newspaper claims to have been assaulted and briefly abducted by plainclothes government thugs who allegedly threatened to kill him if he continued to criticize the government.

Violent clashes erupt between Muslims and Coptic Christians in a town in Minya province in a dispute over the building of a Christian church in the predominantly Muslim town.

issuenote: Tens of thousands of supporters of The Egyptian Movement for Change organize numerous protests across Egypt for several months calling for democratic reforms and an end to President Hosni Mubarak's reign.
A suicide bomber detonates a bomb in the Khan al-Khalili market, a popular tourist spot in downtown Cairo, killing four people, including two French citizens, an American, and the bomber.
notes: It seems as if tourists were the target, but this is not certain as the motives of those involved in the attack are unclear.

issuenote: More than 50 journalists protest in front of Cairo's press syndicate, calling for the annulment of a one-year libel sentence against three fellow reporters who wrote stories critical of Egypt's housing minister.

A group of liberal university professors calling themselves Professors for Change hold two silent demonstrations at Cairo University and Minya University, demanding freedom from government and police interference on university campuses.

Hundreds of students at Minya University take part in an Islamist-led demonstration for the repeal of emergency legislation and the regulations that control student unions.
Around 15,000 members and supporters of the Muslim Brotherhood stage an impromptu protest outside the doctor's syndicate in Tanta, calling for comprehensive political reform.

actor1: Suspect in April 7 bomb attack and his female relatives
issuenote: A suspect in the April 7 suicide bombing in a downtown Cairo market blows himself up as he leaps off a bridge during a police chase; 7 people are injured in the explosion.
notes: Again, it seems as if tourists were the target, but the motive behind these attacks are unclear.

issuenote: Thousands of Muslim Brotherhood supporters gather in Alexandria and later in Cairo to denounce the mass arrests of MB supporters in recent days and to demand the detainees' release.
Thousands of Muslim Brotherhood supporters gather in Alexandria and later in Cairo to denounce the mass arrests of MB supporters in recent days and to demand the detainees' release.
Dozens of supporters of President Hosni Mubarak and his ruling National Democratic Party rally outside the Journalists' Syndicate in downtown Cairo.

target1: President Hosni Mubarak and his ruling National Democratic Party
issuenote: Twenty-six lawmakers, including opposition presidential candidate Ayman Nour of the al-Ghad (Tomorrow) party, walk out of a parliamentary session in protest after voting against a controversial constitutional amendment.
About 2,000 Muslim Brotherhood members protest in front of a mosque in the Gharbiya province north of Cairo, calling for reform of Egypt's religious institutions.
More than 100 lawyers stage a demonstration at their syndicate in Cairo, calling for the release of detainees arrested in a massive crackdown against the Muslim Brotherhood.

Some 13,000 Muslims in Alexandria and Cairo stage protests to demand an official apology from the United States for the alleged desecration of the Qur'an by U.S. military prison interrogators in Guantanamo Bay.

Hundreds of men and women rally at the Press Syndicate, calling for reform and outraged at the assaults on women during the May 25 referendum vote by men alleged to be working for the ruling National Democratic Party.
Around 1,250 anti-government protesters gather at Cairo's highest court in two separate demonstrations to protest the detention of four supporters of the pro-reform Kefaya (Enough) movement.

Relatives of 37 detainees identified by Human Rights Watch and the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) as being imprisoned beyond their official period of detention gather outside the Lawyers' Syndicate in Cairo to protest.

A few hundred supporters of opposition leader Ayman Nour of the al-Ghad party gather outside a the trial of Nour for allegedly forging some of the signatures needed for government approval to form his party.

Some 300 journalists gather in front of the parliament building in a demonstration organized by the Press Syndicate to protest against a new law that would send journalists to jail if found guilty of publishing false news reports.

actor1: Relatives of detained Muslim Brotherhood members
issuenote: About 200 wives and children of 1,200 detained Muslim Brotherhood members stage a peaceful sit-in outside the state prosecutor's office in Cairo to demand the release of their family members.
Three British citizens and one Dutch man imprisoned in the Mazraat al-Tura prison outside Cairo go on hunger strike to protest abuse by guards and prison officials.
Multiple bomb blasts hit several hotels packed with European and Egyptian tourists in Egypt's Red Sea resort town of Sharm el-Sheikh, killing at least 88 people and wounding 119.

issuenote: Residents of Sharm el-Sheikh demonstrate against terrorism a day after their city was rocked by multiple bomb attacks, allegedly by a group calling itself the Al-Qaeda Organization in the Levant and Egypt, which killed 88 people.

target1: Al-Qaeda Organization in the Levant and Egypt

Colleagues of a journalist suspected to have been abducted by security forces for assaulting a security officer during a recent pro-reform rally held by the Kefaya (Enough) movement hold a sit-in at the Press Syndicate's Cairo offices.
A roadside bomb explodes near a military base where international peacekeeping troops charged with protecting the peace treaty between Israel and Egypt, injuring two Canadian peacekeepers.

Hundreds of members of the Kefaya movement, a pro-reform coalition, demonstrate in front of the Lawyers' Syndicate in Cairo to encourage Egyptian judges to insist on stronger powers in supervising next week's presidential elections.

About 1,000 protesters march to a state security headquarters in western Cairo where some political detainees have died, chanting slogans and demanding the release of detainees, many of whom are members of the banned Muslim Brotherhood.

Over 500 artists, writers, and intellectuals stage two separate protests against Farouk Hosni, Egypt's culture minister, who offered his resignation in the wake of a September 5 fire in a state-run theater in Beni Suef that killed 42 people.  T

issuenote: After Palestinian and Egyptian border guards seal off the border between Egypt and the Gaza Strip with barbed wire fencing and concrete barriers, Palestinian crowds throw stones at Egyptian and Palestinian border police.

target1: United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)
issuenote: More than 2,000 Sudanese refugees stage a three-month sit-in at a Cairo park less than 200 meters from the Cairo office of the UNHCR, criticizing the UNHCR of failing to help resettle them in the West.

About 20 members of the pro-reform Kefaya (Enough) movement who were setting up a stage for a state security-approved conference on citizens' rights in the northern Nile Delta city of Damanhur are attacked by pro-govt. thugs.
Thousands of Islamist university students affiliated with the Muslim Brotherhood stage protests on campuses calling for greater freedom on campuses and in national politics.
Tensions between Muslims and Coptic Christians over the DVD release of a Christian play deemed offensive to Islam erupt into violence.
Egyptian police clash with 30 demonstrators, most of them wives, mothers, and children of political detainees, who had gathered outside the Interior Ministry to demand the release of their relatives.
Two journalists covering the parliamentary elections are violently attacked in two separate incidents by unknown assailants who were apparently angered by the journalists' coverage of the elections.

At least 3,000 Muslim Brotherhood supporters stage a demonstration outside the Mustafa Mahmoud mosque in Cairo to protest against the rigged results of the November 9 parliamentary vote; six demonstrators are arrested.
Supporters of the ruling National Democratic Party intimidate and in some cases assault Muslim Brotherhood members and other voters at polling stations around the country.
Several thousand Muslim Brotherhood supporters demonstrate in front of the main counting  center for the Cairo district of Nasr City after polls close on the day of a runoff parliamentary election.

Angry supporters of an independent parliamentary candidate torch the headquarters of the ruling National Democratic Party in the low-income Imbaba district of Cairo after learning that their candidate had lost.

Massive, widespread violence erupts at dozens of polling stations across the country during the second round of parliamentary elections as Muslim Brotherhood supporters, police, and National Democratic Party-hired thugs clash.
notes: Death toll reports vary from 1-3. Npart is an estimate and may be higher.

issuenote: Security forces open fire with live ammunition and use tear gas and batons to block opposition voters from casting their ballots at polling stations in opposition strongholds during a second runoff parliamentary election.
notes: Police blamed the Muslim Brotherhood for sparking the violence, but most reports indicate this was not the case and that MB supporters threw stones only in response to violence by police.  I coded these attacks on police by opposition supporter

issuenote: Hundreds of supporters of opposition leader Ayman Nour of the al-Ghad (Tomorrow) party hold multiple demonstrations outside the courtroom where Nour is on trial for forgery charges.
Groups of opposition voters angered at police using tear gas and rubber bullets to block them from voting in the final runoff in Egypt's three-stage parliamentary elections attack police with stones.

Detained opposition leader Ayman Nour of the al-Ghad party, on trial for forgery in what many outside observers view as an attempt by the ruling party to eliminate a political threat, goes on hunger strike to protest his detention.

An altercation between a Muslim and a Christian results in the death of the Muslim.  Muslim villagers later attack the Abu Sifin church and several Christian homes and loot several shops before authorities restore order.

A few hundred supporters of the Kefaya (Enough) movement and its various offshoots demonstrate in central Cairo to protest against the legitimacy of parliamentary elections which it claims were fixed.
Hundreds of angry Palestinians stream across the border from Gaza into Egypt after militants with stolen bulldozers break through a border wall.
Violence erupts between Muslims and Coptic Christians in the town of Al-Udaysat when Muslims torch a Coptic-owned guest house being used as a church without the proper approval from authorities.

Libyan soccer fans at the Cairo International Stadium rip plastic seats from the stands and hurl them at Egyptian riot police during a game between Egypt and Morocco in the Africa Cup of Nations soccer tournament.

A series of street protests by hundreds of people employed in the poultry and related industries take place after a bird flu outbreak prompts the government to order the large-scale culling of birds and to allow more frozen poultry imports.

issuenote: Some 50 supporters of a rebel faction within the liberal Wafd opposition party seize control of the party's headquarters and open fire on some 700 Wafd party loyalists.

A psychologically disturbed man fatally stabs an elderly Coptic Christian and wounds at least five other worshippers outside several Coptic churches in Alexandria, sparking three days of rioting and violent clashes between Muslims and Copts.

Three bombs rip through a promenade in Dahab, a resort town located on the Sinai peninsula, killing at least 24 Egyptian and foreign tourists, including a five-year-old German child.

Some 40 anti-globalization activists protest at the World Economic Forum being held in the resort town of Sharm el-Sheikh.

Pro-reform activists gather outside the Qasr al-Nil police station in Cairo to denounce the alleged torture and sexual abuse of two fellow activists detained there after a May 25 rally; at least three of the protesters are arrested.

Police use tear gas to disperse hundreds of villagers in the town of Dafash in Minya province who were protesting the fatal stabbing of a fellow Coptic Christian by a Muslim man over a land dispute between the two men.
Some 2,000 Muslim Brotherhood members protest outside a courthouse in Zagazig in support of a senior Brotherhood member on trial there.

Several dozen members of the Journalists' Syndicate demonstrate in front of the syndicate's main offices in Cairo to express their solidarity with three colleagues on trial for denouncing alleged fraud.

Thousands of demonstrators gather in multiple demonstrations, some organized by the Muslim Brotherhood, in Cairo and the northern province of Damietta to denounce the Israeli offensive in Gaza and to call for a holy war against Israel.

Palestinian militants firing guns force open a border gate between Gaza and Egypt, allowing at least 600 Palestinians stream into Egypt.  Egyptian border police used tear gas and dogs to try to disperse the crowd.

Numerous demonstrations take place in Cairo in protest against the Israeli incursion into Lebanon as thousands of demonstrators call on Arab governments to act to stop the fighting, denounce the United States, and express  support for Hezbollah

Students at Helwan University protest against a university ban on wearing the niqab--the full-face veil worn by some Muslim women that allows only the eyes to show--inside the women's residence halls.

About 3,000 workers at Egypt's largest shipyard go on strike after the death of a colleague who was killed in a crane accident the day before.  The workers demanded better working conditions and full compensation for the victim's family.

Tens of thousands of ANC supporters march to demand free electioneering and to show ANC support in the traditional Zulu stronghold.

issuenote: Thousands of Zulus organized by the IFP march to protest the upcoming election.  ANC guards fire on them, killing many.  ANC and Zulus battle across the city.  Fighting continues for several days.

A bombing spree perpetrated by whites.  On 4/24, a car bomb kills 9 people in Johannesburg near the ANC headquarters.  On 4/25, a bomb destroys a taxi stand used by black commuters in Pretoria.  Another bomb explodes the same day in Gerimston.

Protests escalate to riots.  Clashes with police occur.  Residents demand a flat rate for services and rent, that electricity arrears be written off, and the Noorgesig be merged with Soweto.

Taxi drivers wage war during a two week period over taxi routes.

About 50 PAC protesters turn up to protest a visit by US President Bill Clinton.
Scores of protesters angrily demonstrate several times against a white farmer when he appears in court on charges of murdering a black child.
2 killed in ongoing taxi war.

Scattered political violence between ANC and UDM supporters in advance of the election.

Violence of unknown motive.  Gunmen kill a taxi driver and two passengers.

The NNP and the DP form a coalition in Western Cape to keep the plurality party, the ANC, out of power in the province.  ANC supporters march on the provincial legislature and then riot, attempting to storm the legislature.
The rape and murder of a 14 year old girl triggers mob violence and demonstrations.  The mob demolishes the house where the attack occurred.
300 AIDS activists protest at the US consulate to protest against the high price of drugs from the US.
1000 laid off miners protest against Britain, which has sold off 25 tons of gold and depressed the world gold price.
A feeble picket against job cuts.  Numbers unknown.

actor3: National Education Health and Allied Workers Union

Unknown number of students protest against the management of a technical university, expressing solidarity with other workers who have had issues with management.  The protest escalates to a riot.

notes: End date is estimated.  Applied to the estimated day when Durban Roodepoort Deep fires 9000 striking miners.

issuenote: Gunmen shoot and kill nine people at a house accused of harboring criminals.

A COSATU backed general strike over wages in the public sector.  As many as 800,000 people strike and at least 100,000 march in cities around South Africa.
About 1000 IFP supporters march to protest the denial of amnesty to IFP members from the government's Truth and Reconciliation Committee.
A black soldier goes on a shooting spree and kills several of his white colleagues in a racially motivated attack.
Police fire live rounds and teargas at a crowd of 2000 at a racially charged funeral.

Unknown bombers set off a bomb at a bar frequented by gays.
Dozens of Afrikaner protesters demonstrate against a state visit by the Queen, demanding that Britain apologize for the Boer War.

Community members attack a gang, the Terrible Josters, killing 3.  Another person is killed when shot by police.  1000 people then march on the police station demanding they be allowed to burn the gang member's bodies.

One day general strike observed by hundreds of thousands of people.  Protests erupt in most of the major cities.  Workers demand payments for laid off workers and try to force the government to slow the pace of tariff reductions.
Residents protest against warring taxi drivers, clash with police.  1 dies.
Students riot to protest the expulsion of 700 students.  Police use deadly force, killing one.
notes: Deaths blamed on police brutality fall 10 percent to 681 in the 1999-2000 fiscal years.

issuenote: Bus drivers march to the Western Cape provincial parliament to demand government action to end a turf war between taxi drivers that has killed two bus drivers.
South African investigators shut down an investment company, accusing it of being a pyramid scheme.  Thousands of investors protest against the government for months afterward.
A small group of protesters demonstrates against a visit by the chief of the IMF.  Numbers unknown.
20 activists from Act Up protest against the WHO, accusing it of selling out to pharmaceutical companies.
7 die in a turf war between gangs.
notes: 40 have died since the beginning of May in Gang violence.

A bomb explodes near a Mosque and an opposition party meeting.

A car bomb explodes outside a caf?.
Between 9,000 and 10,000 workers strike at six platinum mines over a wage dispute.

A bomb explodes outside an opposition party office.
The SACP organizes protests around the country against the banks, alleging that they are not doing enough to fight poverty.
12000 people march to government headquarters demanding that the government take action against crime.
Irate South African soccer fans begin rioting after Nigeria scores a goal.  Police arrive and fire tear gas into the crowd.

Trade unionists demonstrate at the border crossing to push for democracy in Swaziland.

Hundreds of farmers burn tires and blockade roads to protest delays in a decision on their land claim.
Commuters riot at a train station when some trains are late.  They start a fire, burning several buildings.

Thousands in poor townships and cities across the country protest and riot against poor living conditions, including poor access to housing and basic services.  Police in the townships around Cape Town use tear gas and rubber bullets.

Several hundred people demonstrate against plans by Britain's Barclays to return to retail banking in South Africa, where it was infamous for links to the Apartheid regime.

Hundreds of township protesters demonstrate against lack of housing and access to basic services, threaten to riot.

Workers at a supermarket giant strike for better salaries.
Thousands of municipal workers strike across the country, with thousands marching in cities nationwide.
The first national strike in the gold mining industry in 18 years.  Over 100,000 miners strike for higher wages.
Close to 80,000 workers stage a national strike against municipal governments across the country.  Riots erupt in several cities, triggering police action with stun grenades and rubber bullets.
Protests occur during a court appearance by dismissed Deputy President Jacob Zuma, who is charged with rape.

30,000 Muslim protesters demonstrate against Danish cartoons depicting Mohammed.

As the rape trial for South Africa's ousted deputy president resumes, supporters and opponents gather outside the courthouse to protest.
Metrorail workers strike during a  restructuring of the parastatal Metrorail, fearful that the plan will jeopardize their pensions.

A rally by the SACP calls for the end to a graft charge leveled against sacked deputy president Jacob Zuma.

Thousands march through Cape Town to Parliament to demand sanctions against Israel as a result of its campaign in Lebanon.  They carry pictures of the leader of Hezbollah.

Dozens of activists briefly occupy offices in the provincial government in Cape Town, then march to the Human Rights Commission to pressure it to play a bigger role in securing treatment for AIDS patients.
TAC stages a protest to demand the resignation of the country's health minister due to his response to the AIDS epidemic.
200 protesters protest against the graft trial of Jacob Zuma.
Taxi drivers riot to protest police harassment.

2000 people organized by the Democratic Alliance protest against a plan by the ANC to eliminate the mayoral post in Cape Town and replace it with a committee, thus giving the ANC control over Cape Town.
ANC stages a demonstration to protest against lack of service delivery in poor suburbs.  This protest occurs to counter the DA protest from a day prior.
Hundreds protest against child killers as a man appears in court over the killing of a girl.
Hundreds protest against child killers as a man appears in court over the killing of a girl.

Riots of unknown size in Free State.  Rioters protest poor living conditions in the projects and poor service delivery.  An ANC councilor is hacked to death.
About 200,000 workers strike for higher pay.
Riots of unknown size in Johannesburg's townships over conditions in the housing projects.
500 tenants of a housing project march on parliament to protest shoddy construction and high rent.

Construction workers building the stadium for the 2010 World Cup strike over poor pay.

A protest organized by the DUP in opposition to the Islamist backed military government.  The protest escalated with the demonstrators throw Molotov cocktails.  The police repress with tear gas.
